{
    "analysis": "The prior step loaded all telemetry and produced compact aggregates. metric.csv, trace.csv and log.csv cover the incident time range (earliest 2024-01-24T18:58:00+00:00 to latest 2024-01-24T19:22:00+00:00). error_logs.csv is empty. Many component-KPI pairs exist in metric.csv (cpu, mem, diskio, socket, latency-50/90, workload) across multiple ts-* services. trace.csv contains many traces, including traces from root to ts-admin-* and trace entries for ts-user-service and ts-travel2-service. We need to proceed with metric threshold calculation (global P95 per component-KPI) and then detect anomalies inside the incident window to narrow candidate faulty components. No metric-level thresholds have been computed yet.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 threshold for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair across the entire available series (do NOT filter by incident window for threshold calculation). Parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True) as usual. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC to 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC (inclusive). For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) pair, produce a compact table with these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window, earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window / global_p95). Sort the table by points_exceeding_p95_in_window desc, then by ratio_max_to_p95 desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Return the table only (do not print full raw series)." }

{
    "analysis": "Previous step produced file/column inventories and showed metric/trace/log coverage for the incident window, but the Executor failed to compute global thresholds and windowed anomaly aggregates. We still need global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) calculated on the full metric series (explicitly before any window filtering) and then windowed counts of threshold breaches to narrow candidate faulty components. error_logs.csv is empty so logs may be the secondary source after metrics and traces.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute the global P95 of the value using the entire available series (do NOT filter by incident window for this calculation) and record total_points_full. Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) produce these columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_p95, total_points_full, points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window (value > global_p95), earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (the earliest timestamp in window where value > global_p95, else blank), max_value_in_window, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window / global_p95; if global_p95==0 set ratio to NaN). Sort the output by points_exceeding_p95_in_window descending then ratio_max_to_p95 descending. Limit to top 20 rows. Return only that summarized table (CSV-like or dict)."
}

{
    "analysis": "Metric P95 analysis (previous step) computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and showed many services had brief spikes during the incident window. The top metric offender by relative severity is ts-assurance-service (cpu) with ratio ~3.03 and earliest exceedance at 2024-01-24T18:58:00+00:00. However, many other services (cpu, workload, latency, socket) also show breaches. According to the workflow, we must now use traces to localize which faulty service is the most downstream faulty component in call chains and thereby identify the root-cause component among multiple metric-flagged services. We have not yet computed global thresholds or anomalies for trace features.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) compute the global P95 of value across the entire available series (do NOT filter by the incident window for threshold calculation). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, trace_name) output a compact summary table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, total_points_full, points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window (value > global_p95), earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window / global_p95; set NaN if global_p95==0). Sort rows by points_exceeding_p95_in_window desc then ratio_max_to_p95 desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Return only that summarized table." }

{
    "analysis": "We have computed global P95 per (cmdb_id, kpi_name) and found many services (cpu, workload, latency, socket) with brief threshold breaches during the incident window. Trace analysis showed matching short-lived latency spikes on several inter-service calls (notably ts-basic-service ↔ ts-price-service and ts-inside-payment-service ↔ ts-payment-service). At metric level most candidates only had 2 breach points in the 25-point window — these may be isolated spikes. To identify true faults we must detect consecutive breach sequences (faults), filter out isolated single-point spikes, and measure severity (max / P95) and duration. This will help decide the most likely root-cause component(s) to examine with traces/logs next.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the entire series (do NOT filter by window for P95). Then filter metric rows to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) identify consecutive sequences where value > global_p95. For each sequence produce: cmdb_id, kpi_name, seq_start_timestamp_utc, seq_end_timestamp_utc, seq_length (number of consecutive points), max_value_in_seq, global_p95, ratio_max_to_p95. Filter out sequences with seq_length == 1 (i.e., drop isolated single-point spikes). Return a compact table of these sequences, sorted by seq_length desc then ratio_max_to_p95 desc, limit to top 20 rows. If no sequences remain, return an empty table indicator." }

{
    "analysis": "We filtered metric anomalies to multi-point sequences (all seq_length=2) and produced a ranked list of metric-fault candidates (top CPU spikes: ts-notification-service, ts-admin-route-service, ts-inside-payment-service, ts-food-map-service, plus payment/order/price/travel-related KPIs). Trace-level P95 analysis independently found short-lived latency spikes on several inter-service calls, notably ts-basic-service ↔ ts-price-service and ts-inside-payment-service ↔ ts-payment-service, with earliest exceedances clustered ~19:08–19:13 UTC. According to the root-cause rules, when multiple service-level faults exist we must use traces to find the most downstream faulty service within call chains. We still need a targeted trace-to-metric correlation: for the top metric-fault candidate services, identify traces involving them that also exceeded their trace P95 inside the incident window and determine whether those trace exceedances place the candidate as a downstream faulty service in call chains.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) across the entire available series (do NOT filter by window for P95 calculation). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. Within the filtered traces, keep only rows where trace_name contains any of these service tokens: ts-inside-payment-service, ts-payment-service, ts-price-service, ts-basic-service, ts-order-other-service, ts-travel2-service, ts-preserve-other-service, ts-contacts-service, ts-assurance-service, ts-auth-service. For each unique (cmdb_id, trace_name) matching the filter, output a compact summary table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_p95, points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window (value > global_p95), earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window/global_p95; set NaN if global_p95==0). Sort by points_exceeding_p95_in_window desc then ratio_max_to_p95 desc. Limit to top 20 rows. Return only that summarized table." }

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: computed global P95 thresholds for metrics and traces, filtered the incident window, detected anomalies, and extracted fault candidates by finding consecutive metric exceedances (all were 2-minute sequences). Trace analysis independently shows short-lived latency spikes, with the largest relative increases on basic↔price and payment-related call paths. To localize the root cause we must correlate metric-level faults with trace-level downstream faults: specifically, find traces that place a metric-flagged service as the downstream (called) service and check whether those traces also exceeded their trace P95 at the same time window. This will allow selecting the most downstream faulty service in call chains. Logs (error_logs.csv is empty) can be checked next if necessary.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full available series (do NOT limit to the incident window for P95). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. From this filtered set, select trace series whose trace_name mentions any of these services as the target or source: ts-price-service, ts-payment-service, ts-inside-payment-service, ts-order-other-service, ts-travel2-service, ts-preserve-other-service, ts-contacts-service, ts-assurance-service, ts-auth-service, ts-ticket-office-service. For each matching trace series produce a compact summary table with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, matched_service (the token matched from the list), points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window (value > global_p95), earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, global_p95, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window/global_p95; NaN if global_p95==0). Sort rows by points_exceeding_p95_in_window desc then ratio_max_to_p95 desc. Limit to top 20 rows. Return only that summarized table."
}

{
    "analysis": "We must restrict root-cause candidates to the allowed service set (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service). Previous analysis considered many services but did not enforce this constraint. From earlier outputs there are signs of short (2-minute) metric spikes and trace latency spikes that involve some of these allowed services (e.g., ts-order-service metrics and traces, ts-route-service traces, ts-train-service disk I/O sequence, ts-travel-service metric entries). To localize the root cause correctly we need to focus only on these five services and determine which of them had multi-point metric faults inside the incident window, and how severe/early those faults were.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) using the entire available series (do NOT filter by the incident window for P95). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. Keep only rows where cmdb_id is one of: ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service. For each (cmdb_id, kpi_name) identify consecutive sequences where value > global_p95. Exclude sequences of length 1. For each remaining sequence return a compact table with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, seq_start_timestamp_utc, seq_end_timestamp_utc, seq_length, max_value_in_seq, global_p95, ratio_max_to_p95. Sort by seq_length desc then ratio_max_to_p95 desc. Limit output to top 20 rows. Return only that summarized table."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous step we narrowed candidates to the authorized service set (ts-auth-service, ts-order-service, ts-route-service, ts-train-service, ts-travel-service) and identified multi-point metric faults (all 2-minute sequences). The largest relative deviation among these was ts-train-service diskio at 2024-01-24T18:58→18:59 UTC (ratio≈1.42) and the next-largest was ts-order-service latency at 19:00→19:01 UTC (ratio≈1.27). Other modest multi-point anomalies (socket, mem, workload) occurred later (~19:20–19:22). According to the localization rules, the root cause should be the service with the earliest and/or most significant deviation, unless trace data shows it is upstream of another downstream faulty service. We therefore need to confirm via traces whether ts-train-service (and the other candidates) appear as downstream faulty services in call chains at those times and whether trace latency spikes align with the metric faults. This will let us choose the most downstream faulty service as the root cause.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load trace.csv and parse timestamp with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True). Compute global P95 for each (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the entire series (do NOT filter by the incident window for P95). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2024-01-24 18:55:46 UTC through 2024-01-24 19:25:46 UTC inclusive. From the filtered traces, keep only series whose trace_name mentions any of these services: ts-train-service, ts-order-service, ts-travel-service, ts-auth-service, ts-route-service. For each matching (cmdb_id, trace_name) produce a compact summary with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, matched_service (which of the five it contains), direction ('to' if trace_name contains 'to_ts-<service>' else 'from' if contains 'from_ts-<service>' else 'other'), global_p95, points_in_window, points_exceeding_p95_in_window (value > global_p95), earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc (if any), max_value_in_window, ratio_max_to_p95 (max_value_in_window/global_p95; NaN if global_p95==0). Sort results by earliest_exceedance_timestamp_utc ascending then ratio_max_to_p95 descending. Limit to top 20 rows and return only that summarized table."
}

Review: Across metrics, traces, and logs within 2024-01-24 18:55:46 → 19:25:46 UTC we found short (2-minute) anomalies. The earliest and largest relative anomaly among the allowed services was a disk I/O spike on ts-train-service at 2024-01-24T18:58:00Z (max/p95 ≈ 1.42); ts-order-service latency increased shortly after (~19:00), consistent with downstream impact. Logs show transient row_count/throughput increases but no error_count spikes, supporting resource contention (I/O) rather than application errors.

